description.narrative:
Den föreslagna insatsen stödjer genomförandet av Europarådets strategiska handlingsplaner i sex länder inom det Östliga Partnerskapet: Armenien, Azerbaidzjan, Georgien, Moldavien, Ukraina och Vitryssland, under perioden 2019-2023.

Den föreslagna insatsen bygger på resultat av tidigare samarbete och på dialog med respektive svensk ambassad. Budgetanslaget till respektive handlingsplan tar också hänsyn till det totala beloppet som tillhandahålls av andra givare, bland annat EU, Norge och Danmark. Den svenska regeringens ökade fokus på demokrati och mänskliga rättigheter har gjort det möjligt för ett mer generöst budgetanslag till Europarådet än vad som tidigare planerats.  

Den föreslagna insatsen stödjer genomförandet av följande strategiska handlingsplaner:

Europarådets handlingsplan för Armenia 2019-2022;
Europarådets handlingsplan för Azerbaijan 2018-2021;
Europarådets handlingsplan för Belarus 2019-2021; 
Europarådets handlingsplan för Georgia 2016-2019 (2020-2023);
Europarådets handlingsplan för the Republic of Moldova 2017-2020;
Europarådets handlingsplan för Ukraine 2018-2021.

Handlingsplanerna har tagits fram i nära samarbete med nationella myndigheter och intressenter inom civila samhället. Aktuella områden ligger i linje med de svenska målen för reformsamarbetet i Östeuropa och utgör, tillsammans med Europarådets mervärde, en grund för strategiskt samarbete mellan Sida och Europarådet.

Även om prioriteringarna varierar från land till land, avser handlingsplanerna att främja mänskliga rättigheter och värdighet, säkerställa sociala rättigheter, säkerställa rättvisa, stärka rättsstatsprincipen, motverka hot mot rättsstatsprincipen, stärka den demokratiska styrningen, främja innovation samt främja deltagande och mångfald. Handlingsplanernas inriktning stöder främst revideringen av lagstiftnings- och institutionella ramar i linje med Europarådets standarder och effektiviteten hos reformerade och nyetablerade demokratiska institutioner som bidrar till genomförandet av Europakonventionen om mänskliga rättigheter och andra CoE standarder.

The Sida funded programme will support the CoEs country Action Plans in the EaP region, i.e.  Armenia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Georgia, Moldova and Ukraine. The suggested budget totals 79 MSEK, during the period 2019-2023. The allocations for respective country are as follows: Ukraine 29 MSEK; Georgia 20 MSEK; Armenia 20 MSEK; Moldova 5 MSEK; Azerbaijan 3 MSEK; and Belarus 2 MSEK. 

The suggested new framework agreement is based on positive results of previous cooperation and dialogue with respective Swedish embassy as to the relevance of the CoE in respective country. The total Sida budget allocations made to the respective Action Plan also considers the total amount provided by other donors, among others EU, Norway and Denmark. The increased focus on democracy and human rights by the Swedish government has allowed for a more generous budget allocation to the CoE than previously foreseen. 

The suggested programme with CoE supports the implementation of the following strategic programming documents and respective new Action Plan under preparation:

The Council of Europe Action Plan for Armenia 2019-2022;
The Council of Europe Action Plan for Azerbaijan 2018-2021;
The Council of Europe Action Plan for Belarus 2019-2021; 
The Council of Europe Action Plan for Georgia 2016-2019 (2020-2023);
The Council of Europe Action Plan for the Republic of Moldova 2017-2020;
The Council of Europe  Action Plan for Ukraine 2018-2021.

The key sectors included, although priorities vary for each country, are promoting human rights; promoting human rights and dignity; ensuring social rights; ensuring justice; strengthening the rule of law; countering threats to the rule of law; strengthening democratic governance and fostering innovation; promoting participation and diversity. The focus of the Action Plans primarily supports the revision of legislative and institutional frameworks in line with the CoE standards and the efficient functioning of reformed and newly established democratic institutions contributing to the implementation of the European Convention of Human Rights (ECHR) and of other CoE standards.

Armenia
- More effective application of the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR) in criminal cases as shown by a survey of legal professionals;
- Media guidelines for journalists on violence against women and domestic violence;
- More effective practical steps towards an enhanced asset declaration system through the drawing up of the draft Law on Civil Forfeiture of Illegal Assets (second version of the draft law incorporating most of the Council of Europes recommendations).
Azerbaijan 
- Azerbaijan ratified the Council of Europe Convention on the Protection of Children against Sexual Exploitation and Sexual Abuse. A Gap Analysis of legislation, policies and practices aimed at preventing and combating online child sexual exploitation and abuse and strengthening multi-sectorial co-operation was conducted;
- A roadmap of actions for improving the criminal justice system was drafted; if accepted by the national authorities, it may serve as a useful instrument for further dialogue between Azerbaijan and the Committee of Ministers of the Council of Europe (CM), with a view to adopting the necessary measures for implementing the relevant European Court of Human Rights (ECtHR) judgments;
- The Azerbaijan Press Council adopted amendments to its Code of Professional Ethics, introducing a new standard-setting document entitled Protection of the principle of gender equality and non-discrimination.
Belarus 
- A country-specific project on human rights in biomedicine was finalised at the beginning of 2019. The executive, legislative and judicial authorities as well as professionals concerned were made more aware of the Council of Europes human rights standards and work in the field of biomedicine (bioethics), including the Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Dignity of the Human Being with regard to the Application of Biology and Medicine: Convention on Human Rights and Biomedicine;
- With Council of Europe support , the Ministry of Justice has drafted legislative amendments introducing mediation into the codes of civil and commercial procedure. The amendments were submitted to the parliament for adoption in March 2019 and the new law on mediation was adopted in December 2019, thus ensuring the integration of mediation into the court system, mainly in family and commercial cases;
- On 24 June 2019, Belarus signed the Council of Europe Convention on the counterfeiting of medical products and similar crimes involving threats to public health  the Medicrime Convention.
Georgia 
- Adoption of the Code on the Rights of the Child;
- Adoption by the Chief Prosecutors Office of revised guidelines for the prosecution of cases of domestic violence and violence against women;
- Adoption of the 4th Wave legislative package providing for higher standards for judicial appointments, disciplinary proceedings and the functioning of the High Council of Justice and of the High School of Justice by the Parliament of Georgia in December 2019.
Moldavia 
- The adoption of methodological guidelines on conducting visits in places of deprivation of liberty by the Peoples Advocate and the National Preventive Mechanism (NPM);
- First review of the child protection system of the Republic of Moldova, focusing on responses to child sexual abuse and exploitation;
- The initiation of the reform of the Probation Service in line with Council of Europe recommendations as well as strengthening the mechanisms for co-operation between the probation and prison systems.
Ukraine 
- Adoption by the Verkhovna Rada of a revised version of the Law on Misdemeanours;
- Establishment of the State Service of Ukraine on Ethnic Policy and Freedom of Conscience. Once fully functional, it will serve as an institution committed to developing and implementing policies for the protection and inclusion of national minorities and protect minority languages;
- Successful decentralisation reform, with almost 43% of communities amalgamated by the end 2019 in line with recommendations made by the Council of Europe and other international partners.
